We help clients from various industries migrating to the AWS cloud and optimize their operations on it. Practice Areas
•	Serverless and Containerization

Cloud migration or modernization plans are designed in multistage, from lift&shift to cloud native application, so our clients are able to see the result gradually. Experienced with secure, highly scalable, and performance serverless and containerization implementation and the toolset to automate containerized or serverless app deployment, monitoring, troubleshooting, and operation.

We design and implement CI/CD process, Infrastructure as Code to fully automate provision & deployment. To embrace the variety of big data sources. We built high scalable data intake process through Kineses data stream. Then integrate client data sources with AWS Glue or EMR for fast performance ETL process, eventually leverage tools like AWS QuickSight for data visualization.

Dr. Brad Topol is an IBM Distinguished Engineer and Director of AI and Cloud Open Technologies who also serves as IBM’s Chief Developer Advocate.  In his current role, he leads the global IBM team developing open source technologies and working in open communities.  He has overall responsibility for IBM’s open source strategy, upstream development, community building, education, and client initiatives. He leads a development team with responsibility for contributing to and improving several cloud-native and AI open source technologies including Kubernetes, Tekton, OpenTelemetry, Operator Framework, PyTorch, KubeFlow, and KServe/ModelMesh. 

Brad is responsible for ensuring that the IBM Open Technologies team delivers open source enhancements required by IBM’s Business Units and IBM Research while also focusing on contributions that improve the vitality of open source ecosystems.  He leads IBM’s efforts to grow open source committers across the company through awareness, enablement, and training initiatives. 

As IBM’s Chief Developer Advocate, Brad leads IBM’s Developer Advocacy Initiatives including collateral development, client workshops, presence at conferences and meetups.  In addition, Brad has responsibility creating metrics for measuring the efficacy and impact of developer advocates and ensuring that developer advocacy objectives are aligned with IBM Sales goals. He also provides guidance to IBM Clients on the value of open source, inner source, and Open Source Project Office (OSPO) creation.

In addition to leading a large team, Brad has personally served as an OpenTelemetry, Kubernetes, and Operator SDK contributor, and a Kubernetes Doc Maintainer. He is a co-author of Hybrid Cloud Apps with OpenShift and Kubernetes, a book published by O’Reilly Media in 2021. In addition, he is a co-author of Kubernetes in the Enterprise, a book published by O’Reilly Media in 2018. He received a Ph.D. in Computer Science from the Georgia Institute of Technology in 1998.

The NJ Division of Aging Services is evolving to meet the need to deliver accessible and user-friendly technology that provides services to an aging population. Technology is the third key challenging area, only after chronic diseases and interdisciplinary care. We are developing a closed system, that leverages natural language understanding (NLU) and large language models (LLMs) for our application and interaction designs, and have augmented this with custom vocabularies, built for purpose models, and human-in-the-loop (HITL), to make our design easy and accessible for our seniors, community partners and internal staff.  
Our closed models are augmented with New Jersey specific information, that we review and update on a daily basis to ensure that the answers provided are accurate, complete, concise, consistent and consumable. Working sometimes as a data scientist, user researcher or user experience architect, I work with various programs, process and policy subject matter experts, to integrate best practices from both public and private sector prior to this information being introduced to the model. We are currently building and testing build a multilingual contact center that can provide near real-time assistance for a non-English-speaking constituent from an English-speaking agent. This extendable user interface and API, will enable the near real time translation services over text and voice, with Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) with our closed LLMs we are able to provide these multi-language translations to our content management system, other workloads, applications and user interfaces.
We are also implementing intelligent document processing, innovating our case management and constituent services to provide enhanced services to New Jersey's citizens.

column29:
The English Speaking Union arose from the conviction of its founder, Sir Evelyn Wrench and a group of like-minded American and British friends, that maintenance of the close personal and national ties forged during World War I was necessary for the preservation of peace. Sir Evelyn firmly believed that given the opportunity to know one another personally, people who shared a common language would soon discover that they also shared similar values, whatever their differences in nationality or background. 

Founded in 1920, the English-Speaking Union of the United States is a national membership organization with more than 4,000 members organized in 65 Branches across the country. ESU members and volunteers are the pillars of our educational and cultural programs as they work in their local communities to carry the ESU mission forward. Overview:

At the Executive Office of Health and Human Services (EOHHS), we're embarking on an ambitious journey to revolutionize public health insurance access through the One Health initiative. The goal is to streamline and unify the eligibility and enrollment processes for both MAGI and non-MAGI members, transitioning from the legacy MA21 mainframe system to a modern, modular, and more efficient framework.

Key Responsibilities:

-Project Leadership: Spearheading the technical efforts to migrate the MA21 mainframe system (ADABAS/Natural) to the AWS Cloud. This critical step is foundational for the larger goal of modernizing public health insurance access.
-Strategic Planning: Collaborating in the development of EOHHS's strategic plan. This involves an in-depth analysis of the current Medicaid and MA21 operations, pinpointing areas for innovation and improvement.
-System and Operations Mapping: Leading a comprehensive effort to map and understand the existing Medicaid and MA21 systems and operations, setting the stage for their successful transition to the cloud.
-Technical Architecture Management: Overseeing the implementation of technical solutions across various domains - including business processes, systems integration, hardware, and networking - to ensure a seamless and effective migration of the MA21 system to the AWS Cloud.
-Lead Author of RFQ & RFR for the Rehosting Vendors

Impact:

This initiative marks a pivotal step towards the One Health vision, offering a single point of access for individuals and families seeking public health insurance benefits. By modernizing the legacy system, we're not only enhancing efficiency but also ensuring more robust, secure, and scalable infrastructure for future expansions.

I teach the "Artificial Intelligence in Business: Creating Value with Machine Learning" course. 

Harvard DCE Professional & Executive Development now features more than 120 programs across six topic areas, including leadership, business, innovation, marketing, negotiation, and communication in online and on-campus formats. Our dedicated classroom space at One Brattle Square provides on-campus participants with the latest technology and furnishings, and breakout spaces designed to enhance professional learning and networking.

The mission of Harvard DCE Professional and Executive Development is to meet the needs of professionals from the beginning to end of their careers. Our instructors and team members facilitate not just learning, but professional growth and the development of skills our participants need to meet their career goals while providing an exceptional Harvard learning experience.
Harvard is located within the leading center of technology and innovation: Cambridge, Massachusetts. You will learn at one of the world’s finest academic institutions. There is no better place to invest in developing yourself.

Our programs are led by experts from a variety of arenas in the Boston and Harvard communities and beyond. You’ll engage with them in active classroom discussions, activities, and workshops.

You’ll also collaborate with a diverse set of peers to enrich your learning and your professional network. With participants coming from more than 115 different countries and all 50 states, and a variety of industries, you’ll encounter varied perspectives that can help you see your work in new ways.

THE 10 HIDDEN RISKS TO YOUR BUSINESS AND THEN 1 FAST WAY TO FIND THEM
1. Wrong keys in the wrong hands - watch network access very carefully, and don't give good employees the opportunity to bring you down,
2. Bring your own headache - using employee's phones can bring real headaches. They are often lost or stolen, along with your emails and documents.
3. Who's knocking on your backdoor? - cloud services like Dropbox and Gmail are cheap and convenient, but each of these connections is just as easy for someone else to access.
4. Weak or available passwords - Are your passwords a year old? Do you flip over your keyboard to get the password? Is your password "Password1"?
5. Whoa! Back up! - when was your backup image audited? Your backup process audited?
6. Show me the compliance - often the law requires you to protect customer's data and demonstrate compliance or face fines. Especially in California.
7. Update everything - your defenses are only as good as the updates. Are they updated? Are your computers capable of being updated? 
8. "Ghosts" in the machines - inactive users and computers that have ghost profiles on your network represent holes that may be hackable.
9. When IT can't keep up, your business goes down - you may have redundancies, but they are only as good as your policies and your people, how often are they tested and trained?
10. Hiding in the dark - lack of vision into the true state of your technology defenses may leave your business vulnerable.

The way you can do all of these is to ask for a Network Assessment - from your favorite computer guy - or have us audit your network AND your computer guy for free. You get to keep the summary report.

I founded MOLO17 at the age of 20 in what was originally my great-grandmother's apartment, in a small village in the Pordenone area.

Right from the start, the mission was clear: the ambition to be able to bring agile solutions to the enterprise world for the mobilization of data, notoriously segregated within legacy or difficult-to-access systems, with a strong focus on human experience: this is in fact the most important point for us, namely the gratification of the user who benefits from the solutions that the company makes available to him.

It is only with software designed around the person that the person can feel involved in the processes and thus able to unlock more value for the company.

Every year we challenge ourselves by continuously raising the bar of the quality of the services and products we craft, thus embracing new opportunities and crossing different sectors in which to bring our smile and our expertise.

In 2016 we have invented GlueSync, the data replication solutions born to serve the NoSQL world, it is capable of replicating data in real-time from any relational database to Aerospike, Couchbase and MongoDB. Today is being sold across all over the world through an extended network of partners and directly proposed and adopted from major NoSQL database vendors.  

In June 2022 we opened our HQ in North America, in Cupertino, CA in the center of the Silicon Valley area.

MOLO17 is now recognized as the partner of choice for leading NoSQL database vendors.
